Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61.

It is now necessary to correct a mistake in the translation. Schaeferius' book, which was published in 1451, did not contain an eximere from p. 1451 to p. 1510. Instead of eximere, we find on p. 1451 the words (which are a quotation from Demosthenes), and Schaeferus in the margin remarks, "Struck off." To this must be added the following correction: on p. 1510, we read "videam", and this ought to be changed to "exumeam".

Now the good-order and regularity of the whole is very plainly perceived when we reflect that it is the work of a single and singlely wise and good Maker. And if he be good and wise, he must necessarily be one, and there is no possibility of there being more than one. But if there are gods, as we are taught by the Homeric poets and the later writers, and if they have made everything as it is, and have given it all its parts, and have ordained their own regular order, we can never understand how and what they are; and therefore we believe it is most likely that they are all one only, and that their names are

s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. l.

  (The same is recorded by Procopius, Book I, ch. 28.)

  The following is the text of the text itself:

'And he came to Caesarea and there found the high priest sitting by the judgment seat of the hall, and the scribes of the people, and the elders, and other officers; and he went up to him, and saluted him, and said unto him, High priest, may it please your honour:

prediction.sentence:
Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31.

To Eustathius, who speaks of the same matters in his commentary:

"In the text which is to be corrected the sentence is: I speak of it in its place. The original text says: I speak of it in its place, but, in the original, the word in its place should have been in the same case.

"In the original text the word to be corrected has a double meaning: firstly as "to speak" (to speak of a thing) and secondly as "place" (place to speak of a thing). The sentence, therefore, should have been: "I speak of it in its place. It is of its place."

Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula

PRAYER TO THE VENEREAL GOD.

Blessed be the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ, the Father of mercies and God of all comfort, who comforts us in all our tribulation, that we may be able to comfort those who are in any trouble, with the comfort with which we ourselves are comforted by God. For just as the sufferings of Christ are our consolation, so also our comfort ought to be the comfort of those who suffer according to his sake. To which end we do rejoice in our sufferings for Christ’s sake, knowing that suffering the loss of all things is the gain of eternal life. Therefore, my beloved

MADES

The following is a Latin text, copied by the present editors from the MS in the British Library, formerly in the Bodleian Library (Bodleian Ms. 2625), where it was originally written. It has been printed in facsimile from the original manuscript, and is written in a modern language.

Θελήσας, or Thales, an Ionian, who was born in the island of Samos; he studied astronomy and mathematics under Hipparchus, and afterwards taught the same at Athens. He is considered as the discoverer of the laws of gravitation and attraction, and is said to have discovered the secret of the four elements, which he taught his disciples in the following manner. He divided water into two parts: the first part he put into a vessel,

III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντες. p. 2.

prediction.line: On the 1451 papal conclave the cardinals present were,
prediction.sentence:
Ruediger ad Philipp.

Dauid, I am your friend.  And now I beg that you will tell me where the girl is who is in your house, the one whom you have promised to me in return for my money.  For that I have sent you the gold, and the other gold.

The most important thing for us to consider when we think about the past is the fact that we do not live in the present, we live in the past. The history of human beings is written in the past, and this is why the Greeks have such a preoccupation with the past.

This, however, is also the reason why they are also so preoccupied with the future. The present is to them a period of time that is empty, and that has no meaning, that has nothing, and that is empty. CHAPTER XXII.--THE CRUSADE.

I. prediction.sentence:
... and then again, for you do not want to see the truth of it;
but as you will have it, he made the man himself a king,
having an heir, and the said prince was made heir by the father
to the throne.

And, as I said before, when the heir was made, they brought
the father, and the said prince's brother, and the said prince's
daughter before him, and they set the said heir and his brother on
the throne, so that they could not have done otherwise; and they
brought them into his presence. And the prince made them do
their work with his power, and he caused them to be made rulers of
the people.

prediction.sentence:
The emperor Constantine at his death, as is recorded by the history of his nephew, Philip, was found in a dream of old age, seated on the throne of the universe. A small group of persons, who had attended him through life, stood by, to see him die. In the presence of his attendants he opened his eyes, and spoke a single word. It was "Amen."  He died, and the world has been ever since in a state of universal peace.

Text to be corrected:

THE DEANERY OF LANGUAGES

THE DEANERY OF LANGUAGES, in the Vatican, is one of the most important offices of the Holy See. It was founded by Pius IX in 1844 to promote the study of the different languages of the world. From that time, in various ways, the various nations of the earth were drawn to this place in the hope of being aided in their studies of foreign languages. The Dean, as he is called, is one of the two Deans of the College of Cardinals, with the President of the College of Cardinals, and he is the superior of the whole body of the Deans of the College.

s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. l.

  (The same is recorded by Procopius, Book I, ch. 28.)

  The following is the text of the text itself:

'And he came to Caesarea and there found the high priest sitting by the judgment seat of the hall, and the scribes of the people, and the elders, and other officers; and he went up to him, and saluted him, and said unto him, High priest, may it please your honour:

'And he answered and said unto him, What is thy will?

'And he said, What I will that thou do to me, so that, when I am departed, ye may do likewise to
prediction.sentence:
Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31.

To Eustathius, who speaks of the same matters in his commentary:

"In the text which is to be corrected the sentence is: I speak of it in its place. The original text says: I speak of it in its place, but, in the original, the word in its place should have been in the same case.

"In the original text the word to be corrected has a double meaning: firstly as "to speak" (to speak of a thing) and secondly as "place" (place to speak of a thing). The sentence, therefore, should have been: "I speak of it in its place. It is of its place."

prediction.line: The life of Aglaophorus, of Egypt, a Macedonian, who came to Rome in the year that Philip first began to reign. He was a friend of Alexander the Great; and being sent as an envoy to the Roman people by him, he was admitted to the favor of the emperor. Philip, when he had taken Alexandria, was sent for by the senate; but when he came, and found the people with a tumult, he was sent back again by them, and returned to Macedon. Having now a sufficient power, and being a man of great valor, he returned to Rome, and the people were glad to see him. He was of an illustrious family: his father was a general of Alexander; his grandfather was the most famous of the Macedonians; and he was himself a great man, even greater

Philip, when he had taken Alexandria, was sent for by the senate; but when he came, and found the people with a tumult, he was sent back again by them, and returned to Macedon. Having now a sufficient power, and being a man of great valor, he returned to Rome, and the people were glad to see him. man's being.  It is the master of men, and directs them.  He who has
made the best use of art, has made the best use of himself.  The

prediction.sentence:
VI.

  [The Romans, and most other states, as well as cities, are divided into three distinct kinds of government: monarchies, republics, and kingdoms.  The Romans used a kind of republic which was called the monarchy of the equites, that is, the monarchy of the Roman army, and is called thus, because it was instituted by the first Roman king, Romulus.  For when, after the battle of Lake Trasimene, a Roman army was met by the enemy, they were defeated, and as they had no king, they surrendered.  But when they were afterwards re-assembled and made into a monarchy, and had become Romans, their king was Romulus,

ocr.line: the fiery man.’ Essay on L. § 9. p. 12, 2.
ocr.region: the fiery man. Essay on L. §9. P. 12, 2. If τοι is retained in infr. 245, we may read here οἵαν ἐδήλωσας *kar avdpis αἴθονος. The short syllable in αἴθονος is sufficiently supported by at6ova occur- ring in Hesychius in the right alpha- betical order (immediately after alo1). Although αἴθοπος (see v. r1.) may be defended, on the ground that the second part of a compound has sometimes little significance (see esp. infr. 954, κελαι- νῶπαν θυμόν), yet αἴθων, which directly expresses character, is more appropriate here, and has the preponderance of MS. authority in its favour. 222. ἄτλατον οὐδὲ φευκτάν] ‘That can neither be avoided nor endared.’ 225. μεγάλων] ‘Terrible.’ The mari- ners, in their feebleness (supr. 165 foll.), are afraid of the opinion of the host. These words are added as a commenut on οὐδὲ φευκτάν. The consequences of the fact cannot be eluded, since it is known to the host, and magnified by rumour. 226. ὁ pyasus) ‘The formidable power of rumour.’ Supr. 172, & μεγάλα φάτις. μῦθος is the rumour about this particular thing, with a suggestion of rumour in geneial. ἀέξει] Not "exaggerates,’ for the evil could not be exaggerated, but, ‘which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad.’
groundtruth.line: the fiery man. Essay on L. §9. P. 12, 2.
groundtruth.region: the fiery man.’ Essay on L. § 9. p. 12, 2. If τοι is retained in infr. 245, we may read here οἵαν ἐδήλωσας *κατ’ ἀνδρὸς αἴθονος. The short syllable in αἴθονος is sufficiently supported by αἴθονα occur- ring in Hesychius in the right alpha- betical order (immediately after αἶθον). Although αἴθοπος (see v. rr.) may be defended, on the ground that the second part of a compound has sometimes little significance (see esp. infr. 954, κελαι- νώπαν θυμόν), yet αἴθων, which directly expresses character, is more appropriate here, and has the preponderance of MS. authority in its favour. 222. ἄτλατον οὐδὲ φευκτάν] ‘That can neither be avoided nor endured.’ 225. μεγάλων] ‘Terrible.’ The mari- ners, in their feebleness (supr. 165 foll.), are afraid of the opinion of the host. These words are added as a comment on οὐδὲ φευκτάν. The consequences of the fact cannot be eluded, since it is known to the host, and magnified by rumour. 226. ὁ μέγας μῦθος] ‘The formidable power of rumour.’ Supr. 172, ὦ μεγάλα φάτις. μῦθος is the rumour about this particular thing, with a suggestion of rumour in general. ἀέξει] Not ‘exaggerates,’ for the evil could not be exaggerated, but, ‘which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad.’

Odysseus had been wandering for years. Long, long years. He had wandered from place to place, from kingdom to kingdom; and he had seen all the splendour of the world, the splendour of Asia, and the splendour of Greece. But now the time of his wanderings, and of his toils and anxieties, was drawing to its close. He had come to his own. He had found his own.

When he first arrived in Thessaly, at the castle of Menelaus, and when he had asked for the king of the realm, he had been told that he had departed for Troy. And when he asked for his wife Penelope, he had been told that she had also gone to Troy, on account of the presence of Achilles. He had left the castle, and wandered up and down, he knew not where; and had found himself at last, in a deserted village, in a deserted and forsaken part of Thessaly. There, at night, he had heard the rustling of some beast, and had trembled

prediction.sentence:
222.

There is a dispute about the date on which St. Thomas Aquinas wrote his De Doctrina Christiana. Some believe it was written before 1228, the date on which he died; others think it was written after 1228. This controversy is a secondary matter, for we are concerned with a text which, at all events, was written after 1228.

Since the death of Thomas, the Dominicans and the Franciscans took possession of the university of the Sorbonne and established new courses of instruction. They were not long in adopting his method of writing. The work of Thomas was taken up by various students of theology. It became the model for the writings of the new generation.

There is something more than just a rumour that Alexander will leave the army to go home; he has already done so.   This means that the armies will be divided up. prediction.sentence:
222.

There is a dispute about the date on which St. Thomas Aquinas wrote his De Doctrina Christiana. Some believe it was written before 1228, the date on which he died; others think it was written after 1228. This controversy is a secondary matter, for we are concerned with a text which, at all events, was written after 1228.

Since the death of Thomas, the Dominicans and the Franciscans took possession of the university of the Sorbonne and established new courses of instruction. They were not long in adopting his method of writing. The work of Thomas was taken up by various students of theology. It became the model for the writings of the new generation.

of Eusebius’s own exposition of the life of Jesus Christ (Peregrine

Epistle

of Eusebius’s own exposition of the life of Jesus Christ (Peregrine
Pilgrimage), which he had previously drawn from Eusebius’s
Epistle

(“Now therefore, if it seems good to you that Achilles’ tent should be pitched here in the plain, let it be pitched in the plain.”) I do not wish to press you, and I am thankful for your readiness, but it seems to me that you are making a journey to a distant country in search of a bird that you do not even know is there. How can I tell you that a bird has not flown, or that it has flown and is in some place that you have not found it? The same can be said of any kind of animal. Are you looking for a cat which you do not know is alive, or dead? I have not even known that there are any such things as wild horses in these regions. Where, then, would you pitch your tent? Should you pitch it in the middle of the woods, or on the banks of a river, or in some field where there are trees? For there are woods everywhere. But if you pitch your tent on a plain, you may come to find a lion that has been sleeping and will not wake up. Then too you might find it lying on the ground, or under a bush. You do not know that it is there, nor where it is. And if you were to find it lying under a bush, how would you catch it? If it had been awake, it would have rushed away. And how would you catch it if it were asleep? Would you carry it along and let it sleep in your tent? And what should you do with it when you had caught it? Would you keep it as a pet? For if you were to keep it, you would have to feed it, and you would have to give it its share of meat. You would have to put it to sleep, and in the morning you would have to wake it up, and it would be afraid and would run away. How then, are you to get the advantage of taking it alive? This then is the way of a soldier. First of all, you must have good courage, and then you must have excellent intelligence. The first of these you have, but the other is wanting. Are you looking for a cat which you do not know is alive, or dead? I have not even known that there are any such things as wild horses in these regions. Where, then, would you pitch your tent? Should you pitch it in the middle of the woods, or on the banks of a river, or in some field where there are trees? For there are woods everywhere. But if you pitch your tent on a plain, you may come to find a lion that has been sleeping and will not wake up. Then too you might find it lying on the ground, or under a bush. You do not know that it is there, nor where it is. And if you were to find it lying under a bush, how would you catch it? If it had been awake, it would have rushed away. And how would you catch it if it were asleep? Would you carry it along and let it sleep in your tent? And what should you do with it when you had caught it? Would you keep it as a pet? For if you were to keep it, you would have to feed it, and you would have to give it its share of meat. You would have to put it to sleep, and in the morning you would have to wake it up, and it would be afraid and would run away. How then, are you to get the advantage of taking it alive? Are you looking for a cat which you do not know is alive, or dead? I have not even known that there are any such things as wild horses in these regions. Where, then, would you pitch your tent? Should you pitch it in the middle of the woods, or on the banks of a river, or in some field where there are trees? For there are woods everywhere. But if you pitch your tent on a plain, you may come to find a lion that has been sleeping and will not wake up. Then too you might find it lying on the ground, or under a bush. He holds that the true cause of things must be searched for in the same manner as the causes of external phenomena are sought for, viz. by reference to the causes of their effect and not to the effects themselves. And he does not suppose that the soul, as it has a natural and immortal existence, has any other cause of itself except such as belongs to it, but attributes the cause of external phenomena to the soul which is mortal, and the causes of its cause to its own immortality. And, indeed, the nature of the soul has been declared by our predecessors and is now very well known, for it has been demonstrated that it has its own cause in this mortal body

"What must I do, to be delivered from this evil passion?" Socrates asked.
"First," he replied, "make the question clearer: do you wish to be delivered from the passion, or do you want to be delivered from the evil that causes the passion? There is the difference."

For this purpose he told the story of a man who was driven mad by the sight of a beautiful woman, because he could not control the urge to rape her. It was his aim, he said, to be delivered from the evil that caused the passion, and not from the passion itself. To this end he devoted himself to the art of self-restraint, to abstinence, to continence

The alternative is to take ἐπ’ uol as= ‘in my case,’ and βλέψας as epexegetic ; but this is certainly harsh. 846 f. διοίγω: cp. O. T. 1287 διοί- γειν kA6pa, and ib. 1295.—mpdyn, deeds: cp. 21. Pe ἐκκύκλημα is now pushed on through the central door. It was a small stage, but large enough to allow of Ajax being shown surrounded by some of the slaugh- tered animals. The word πράγη in 247, and the language of vv. 351 ff., show that the carnage was represented. Aristides (460-377 BCE) was a Greek statesman who was sent by Alexander the Great to govern Egypt. He was an ally of Ptolemy IV Euergetes of Egypt against the Seleucids of Syria and later an enemy of the Seleucids. He had served in Alexander's army and returned with him to Egypt in 331 BCE. He became the prime minister in 323 and later became the ruler of Egypt. He is remembered as an orator and politician.

Aristides is remembered for his attempt to reform the state bureaucracy. After he was accused of bribery and treason, he decided to commit suicide

prediction.line:
"This picture by Timomachus is thought to have been drawn around the year 600. It is the most famous picture from the School of Athens, because of the beauty of the youth, of the female figure, of the symmetry of the head and of the other details, as well as for the harmony of the whole. The youth is believed to be the hero Heracles, whose statue in the temple of Athena at Olympia was adorned with golden ornaments, and who was known throughout the Greek world as the strongest of men." (from the Schiller Encyclopedia of the Classical Age, edited by K. Scholz)

[PANET. SON]  This discourse of Antisthenes, in which the

preface'. I do this, not because this doctrine has no

be in some sort expounded to the public; and this, more than
any other part, could be done by an interpreter who would
understand that which is concealed in the words, but not
what appears to the naked eye; as, when they that see the
moon shining through a chink in a wall understand not
what the shadow is, but only the wall

ocr.sentence: 34 Zephyrum dicit in plantas nutricium exercere.
ocr.region: πνεύματος ἐπιρροῆῇ ἀέρα ὑγρὸν ἕλκοντες ὥσπερ νήπιοι παῖδες. Pliny H. M. 18. 34 Zephyrum dicit in plantas nutricium exercere. Lucian Bis accus. § 1 rods ἀνέ- μους purovpyowras. We might add Catull. 62. 39 ut flos.. | Quem mulcent aurae, firmat sol, educat imber.—va ψυχὴν ἀτάλλων. Cp. Tr. 144 τὸ γὰρ νεάζον ἐν τοιοῖσδε βόσκεται| χώροισιν αὐ- τοῦ εἰς. (n.). The word ἀτάλλω (which in Il. 13. 27 means ‘to gambol’) bears the sense of ‘cherishing’ in Hom. epigr. 4. 2 νήπιον αἰδοίης ἐπὶ γούνασι μητρὸς ἀτάλλων, and Pind. fr. 214 γλυκεῖά ol καρδίαν drd\oira... | ἐλπίς. The Homeric form in this sense is ἀτιτάλλω, Od. 18. 323 παῖδα ds ἀτίταλλε. The word drdMw may have been sug- gested to Sophocles by a trait in the scene between Hector and Andromachè: II. 6. 400 παῖδ’ ἐπὶ κόλπῳ ἔχουσ’ ἀταλά- φρονα, νήπιον atrws. χαρμονήν might be acc. in appos. with ψυχὴν only; but is better taken as acc. in agpos. with the whole sentence (see on El 130 ἤκετ’ ἐμῶν καμάτων wapa- utio).—The conjecture χαρμονή is no gain. 880 It is strange that exception should have been taken to the parenthetic οἶδα, which is not rare; cp. 938, O. C. 1615, El. 334. — obros.. p: cp. 83, 421.

the author [Lucian] of the satire (ἐνέργεια και ἄλλοις) of Anacreon and Theocritus.

In the scene between Hector and Andromache, Sophocles has represented the poetess as making a reply to Hector, after he had announced to her that his victory was a victory for Troy. But there are indications that Sophocles would rather have given us the impression that the poetess was about to make some complaint to the god; the first word of her reply, then, is ὅπος, which means "god".

The word drdMw may have been sug- gested to Sophocles by a trait in the scene between Hector and Andromache: II. It may be argued that in that scene, in which Hector is about to die, the death-dealing god must be Zeus, or Jupiter, or even Apollo, all of whom are the god of the thunderbolt, and are known in Homer by the

πνεύματος ἐπιρροῆῇ ἀέρα ὑγρὸν ἕλκοντες ὥσπερ νήπιοι παῖδες. Pliny H. M. 18. 34 Zephyrum dicit in plantas nutricium exercere. Lucian Bis accus. § 1 rods ἀνέ- μους purovpyowras. We might add Catull. 62. 39 ut flos.. | Quem mulcent aurae, firmat sol, educat imber.—va ψυχὴν ἀτάλλων. Cp. Tr. 144 τὸ γὰρ νεάζον ἐν τοιοῖσδε βόσκεται| χώροισιν αὐ- τοῦ εἰς. (n.). Hector: I am tired. But I will not yield my place. I know this is my land.
Andromachè: I have never said that it was not your land, but your own people
who killed your father and your brothers.

I am tired. I see a place where I could rest a little bit. I must speak with Andromache
and with Patroclus. I must speak with those who are leading the soldiers in this
war. You, Hector, have the duty to keep them faithful and in good heart.

Andromachè: Hector, you have done what you had to do.

To the north and west the Thessalian mountains rise, to the south they are broken by long strips of plains which in the central portion of the region come down to the river Isthmus of Corinth, but in the northern part they form a broad plateau, reaching to the confines of Thrace. East of the mountains, on the north and west, lie the mountainous districts of Thessaly. The mountains, which are of various types, are of great height, and in their lower parts are covered with pine forests. In the northern part of the region there are extensive plains of moderate elevation, separated from each other by ridges of rock. East of the region of Thessaly is the plain of Macedonia, a plain of comparatively little elevation, extending from a river at the southern extremity of the region to the Gulf of Corinth, with a length of about 150 miles (240 km), and with an average breadth of 20 miles (30 km). In the middle of this plain lies the region of Thessaly. It has an area of about 80 miles (130 km) at its widest, and the average width is about 15 miles (25 km). It is bounded to the north by the river Isthmus of Corinth, and on the west it borders on the Plain of Macedon. At its eastern extremity it reaches to the sea, and is connected with it by two narrow isthmuses (the Gulf of Corinth and the Isthmus of Corinth), each about 15 miles (25 km) wide. East of the region of Thessaly is the plain of Macedonia, a plain of comparatively little elevation, extending from a river at the southern extremity of the region to the Gulf of Corinth, with a length of about 150 miles (240 km), and with an average breadth of 20 miles (30 km). It is bounded to the north by the river Isthmus of Corinth, and on the west it borders on the Plain of Macedon. At its eastern extremity it reaches to the sea, and is connected with it by two narrow isthmuses (the Gulf of Corinth and the Isthmus of Corinth), each about 15 miles (25 km) wide. The central part of the plain is occupied by a large plain, extending from the Isthmus of Corinth to the Isthmus of Corinth, about 65 miles (100 km) wide, but often narrowing to only 20 miles (30 km) at certain points. This plain is separated from the sea by a line of mountains which, with the exception of the ridge which is immediately east of the Isthmus of Corinth, are at a considerable distance from the sea. On the west the mountains rise to a height of 3000 ft (915 m) in the northern plain, and to 7000 ft (2065 m) in the southern plain. The mountains are covered with pine woods. The climate is mild. chief things which we have above to do.  We must consider
first whether it be necessary to make an inventory of the
things themselves; if not, it is sufficient to know that there
is the greatest abundance of those things on our side of the
river; and for the most part on that side which is nearer the
river.  The first is that of the corn, which we possess in
greater quantity and of a better quality on this side; for we
have corn of every sort, not only of wheat, but also of the
barley, which is so good a grain that it makes of itself good
bread

469.  Now at length to speak of that of the three
chief things which we have above to do.  We must consider
first whether it be necessary to make an inventory of the
things themselves; if not, it is sufficient to know that there
is the greatest abundance of those things on our side of the
river; and for the most part on that side which is nearer the
river.  The first is that of the corn, which we possess in
greater quantity and of a better quality on this side; for we
have corn of every sort, not only of wheat, but also of the
barley, which is so good a grain that it makes of itself good
bread

prediction.sentence:
The poet bids us take care of ourselves, though, with a gentle hand, he holds the torch of wisdom.  It is necessary for a wise man to take care of himself.  A person may be wise enough to be able to get along by himself, but the greater the freedom in which he lives, the greater the danger he runs of not taking care of himself.
He advises us to remember that he does not give us his torch to be a guide and leader, but only a torch.  But he urges us on by a kind word, because, as he says, he is a person who knows how to treat those he guides.  He also explains why it is necessary to take care of ourselves.  He says that the wise man will not take care of himself by merely eating and drinking, nor by merely lying on his bed; for these are the works of the unwise and not of the wise

(To Crescens)

I see that the king of Spain has sent a messengers to the Roman emperor. I think, therefore, that you should tell him that I cannot at present come to him. For I am in the midst of a war, and it is my duty to finish this war, and then I must return to Rome.

Crescens, I cannot reply to what you have written about me. But, however, if there is anything that you have said which is not true, let me know what it is, and I will tell the king that you have spoken falsely.

I see that the king of Spain has sent a messengers to the Roman emperor. I think, therefore, that you should tell him that I cannot at present come to him. For I am in the midst of a war, and it is my duty to finish this war, and then I must return to Rome.

Crescens, I cannot reply to what you have written about me. But, however, if there is anything that you have said which is not true, let me know what it is, and I will tell the king that you have spoken falsely.

prediction.sentence:
686.

The Greek word καθόπαιτος(ekstathopoulos, ōstathopoulos), which

has been used to designate the king of Egypt, was also used by the

ancients to designate the governor of Syria and Cilicia. His office

must have been similar to that of the governor of the province of

Cyprus, who was styled χρυσός (chrysois), whence the name of that

province. This word is not found in Plutarch. It does not seem

necessary to note that the office was originally held by a Greek.

prediction.sentence:
686.

The Greek word καθόπαιτος(ekstathopoulos, ōstathopoulos), which

has been used to designate the king of Egypt, was also used by the

ancients to designate the governor of Syria and Cilicia. His office

must have been similar to that of the governor of the province of

Cyprus, who was styled χρυσός (chrysois), whence the name of that

province. This word is not found in Plutarch. It does not seem

necessary to note that the office was originally held by a Greek.

This is the work of an author of the last quarter of the 11th century, who was probably a native of Alpheios (Apulia). It is composed of two books, of which the first contains some fragments of two other works, which are not mentioned by him. The second book is composed of two parts, in each of which some fragments from two other works are introduced.

Book I, Book II

In the first part the poet deals with Menelaos in the character of Simonides the Athenian and the friend of Socrates. He considers that the two works which the poet here mentions, though belonging to the same school, are not on the same subject. He thinks that the one of which he speaks is the work of Simonides Amorges, the other of Menelaos himself. He also thinks that the first part is a continuation of the works of Socrates. He considers that both Simonides and Menelaos have been accused of heresy.

Menelaos, the son of Philip, is said to have come to Athens in the year 955, and, though young, to have attracted the notice of Socrates. He was taken at first into the circle of the Stoics and then of the Sophists. He was accused, and as one of his own pupils was also accused, he was compelled to withdraw from Athens and to travel. He did not return, but is said to have been killed by the Persians at Ctesiphon (see Menelaos).

Simonides Amorges lived in the time of Socrates. He had an estate in Argos. His works have been lost, but he was an adept in eloquence. He is said to have composed a work called the Book of Orations and a work on the soul called the Book of the Soul.

1.  The Song of Pan (in hexameters), and the poem of Arion.
2.  The Song of Phaon (in the same metre), and the poem of Proserpine.
3.  The Song of the Daphoenician Maiden, (in hexameters).
4.  The Song of the Pelasgian Maiden (in the same metre).

It is composed of two books, of which the first contains some fragments of two other works, which are not mentioned by him. The second book is composed of two parts, in each of which some fragments from two other works are introduced.

Book I, Book II

In the first part the poet deals with Menelaos in the character of Simonides the Athenian and the friend of Socrates. He considers that the two works which the poet here mentions, though belonging to the same school, are not on the same subject. He thinks that the one of which he speaks is the work of Simonides Amorges, the other of Menelaos himself. He also thinks that the first part is a continuation of the works of Socrates. He considers that both Simonides and Menelaos have been accused of heresy.

Menelaos, the son of Philip, is said to have come to Athens in the year 955, and, though young, to have attracted the notice of Socrates. He was taken at first into the circle of the Stoics and then of the Sophists. He was accused, and as one of his own pupils was also accused, he was compelled to withdraw from Athens and to travel. He did not return, but is said to have been killed by the Persians at Ctesiphon (see Menelaos).

Simonides Amorges lived in the time of Socrates. He had an estate in Argos. His works have been lost, but he was an adept in eloquence. He is said to have composed a work called the Book of Orations and a work on the soul called the Book of the Soul.

Die Furcht galt den Griechen als Haltpunkt jeder geſellſchaftlichen Ordnung. 1077. γεννήσῃ hat Sopho⸗ kles nach Analogie von φύειν (πώγωνα, πτερά, ὀδόντας) gebraucht. - μέγα proleptiſches Prädikat wie δεινόν 1124. 1080. I § 61, 4, 5. - παρῇ: zu 496. 1083. Es findet ſich ἐξ οὐρίων (πνευμάτων) θεῖν, πλεῖν, φέρεσθαι wie ἐξ οὐρίας πλεῖν, κομίζεσθαι (Beiſpiele bei Lobeck). I § 46, 6, 9, Cu. § 153, 3, Kr. § 83, Ku. § 25, 3. - Der Endreim hebt das Gleich⸗ mäßige des Inhalts. 1090. Vgl. Eur. Phön. 1657 Antigone: ἐγώ σφε θάψω, κἂν ἀπεννέπῃ πόλις. Kreon: σαυτὴν ἄρ’ ἐγγὺς τῷδε συνθάψεις νεκρῷ.

Die Furcht galt den Griechen als Haltpunkt jeder geſellſchaftlichen Ordnung. 1077. γεννήσῃ hat Sopho⸗ kles nach Analogie von φύειν (πώγωνα, πτερά, ὀδόντας) gebraut. — μέγα proleptiſches Prädikat wie δεινόν 1124. 1080. Vgl. Hom. E 351 αἰδομένων ἀνδρῶν πλέονες σόοι ἠὲ πέφανται, Ant.675f. 1081f. 670v .. ταύτην τὴν πόλιν wie Phil. 456 ὅπου . . τούτους τοὺς ἄνδρας. — δρᾶν ἃ βούλεται (willkürlich ſchalten und walten): Subjekt iſt der bei ὑβρίζειν δρᾶν re vorſchwebende allgemeine Begriff (ris) Kr. 1 8 64, 4,5. — zao07: zu 496. 1083. Es findet fih 85 ovoim» (πνευμάτων) Dew, πλεῖν, φέρεσθαι wie ἐξ οὐρίας πλεῖν, κομίζεσθαι (Beiſpiele bei Lobe). In demſelben Sinne ſteht οὔρια θεῖν (mit günſtigem Winde fahren). — πεσεῖν das Futurum wird Durch χρόνῳ ποτὲ („früher oder ſpäter“) vertreten. 1084. xai δέος, auch Furcht, nicht bloß Willkür. — καίριον, zu rechter Zeit ſich ein- ſtellend, heilſam. — Vgl. Aſch. Eum. 920 ἔσθ’ ὅπου To δεινὸν εὖ . . ξυμφέρει σωφρονεῖν ὑπὸ oreveı. 1085 f. Über ἥδεσθαί τι Kr. 1846, 6,9, Cu. 8 153, 3, Kr. 8 83, Ku. 825, 3. — Der Endreim hebt das Gleich⸗ mäßige des Inhalts. 1090. Vgl. Eur. Phön. 1657 Antigone: ἐγώ oe Vapo, x0V ἀπεννέπῃ πόλις. Kreon: σαυτὴν do’ ἐγγὺς τῷδε συνθάψεις νεκρῷ.

groundtruth.region: pareat. 1076. πρόβλημα δ. i. dem nicht etwas, das er fürchtet und ſcheut, vor Augen ſteht.- Der Schol. führt einen Spruch des Epicharm an: ἔνθα δέος, ἐνταῦθα καὶ αἰδώς. Die Furcht galt den Griechen als Haltpunkt jeder geſellſchaftlichen Ordnung. 1077. γεννήσῃ hat Sopho⸗ kles nach Analogie von φύειν (πώγωνα, πτερά, ὀδόντας) gebraucht. - μέγα proleptiſches Prädikat wie δεινόν 1124. 1080. Vgl. Hom. E 351 αἰδομένων ἀνδρῶν πλέονες σόοι ἠὲ πέφανται, Ant. 675 f. 1081 f, ὅπου . . ταύτην τὴν πόλιν wie Phil. 456 ὅπου . . τούτους τοὺς ἄνδρας. - δρᾶν ἃ βούλεται (willkürlich ſchalten und walten): Subjekt iſt der bei ὑβρίζειν δρᾶν τε vorſchwebende allgemeine Begriff (τίς) Kr. I § 61, 4, 5. - παρῇ: zu 496. 1083. Es findet ſich ἐξ οὐρίων (πνευμάτων) θεῖν, πλεῖν, φέρεσθαι wie ἐξ οὐρίας πλεῖν, κομίζεσθαι (Beiſpiele bei Lobeck). In demſelben Sinne ſteht οὔρια θεῖν (mit günſtigem Winde fahren). - πεσεῖν: das Futurum wird durch χρόνῳ ποτὲ („früher oder ſpäter") vertreten. 1084. καὶ δέος, auch Furcht, nicht bloß Willkür. - καίριον, zu rechter Zeit ſich ein⸗ ſtellend, heilſam. - Vgl. Aſch. Eum. 520 ἔσθ’ ὅπου τὸ δεινὸν εὖ . . ξυμφέρει σωφρονεῖν ὑπὸ στένει. 1085 f. Über ἥδεσθαί τι Kr. I § 46, 6, 9, Cu. § 153, 3, Kr. § 83, Ku. § 25, 3. - Der Endreim hebt das Gleich⸗ mäßige des Inhalts. 1090. Vgl. Eur. Phön. 1657 Antigone: ἐγώ σφε θάψω, κἂν ἀπεννέπῃ πόλις. Kreon: σαυτὴν ἄρ’ ἐγγὺς τῷδε συνθάψεις νεκρῷ.

(the main contents). [in modern language]. 1090. A. [in modern language]. 1657

This work, which is a translation of Sophocles' Antigone, appeared as the third of a trilogy with Oedipus Tyrannus and The Tragedy of Oedipus.

The action of Antigone begins with the burial of her brother, Polynices. After the tomb is opened, Antigone and Eteocles discover the body, which Antigone, as the next of kin, is to carry back to the city of Thebes. When the two are summoned by the King, they decide to bury the body secretly. When they are caught by the priests, Polynices' son, Orestes, who had been sent to Thebes to get rid of Antigone, comes to their rescue.

prediction.line:
(the main contents). [in modern language]. 1090. A. [in modern language]. 1657

This work, which is a translation of Sophocles' Antigone, appeared as the third of a trilogy with Oedipus Tyrannus and The Tragedy of Oedipus.

The action of Antigone begins with the burial of her brother, Polynices. After the tomb is opened, Antigone and Eteocles discover the body, which Antigone, as the next of kin, is to carry back to the city of Thebes. When the two are summoned by the King, they decide to bury the body secretly. When they are caught by the priests, Polynices' son, Orestes, who had been sent to Thebes to get rid of Antigone, comes to their rescue.

There are two reasons why we must not be silent regarding the
greatness of the Lord.

(1) The first is that if we do not make a distinction
between the greatness of the Lord and the greatness of man, our own
blessings will be greatly diminished.

(2) The second is that the greatness of the Lord is
a witness to the greatness of man. For if the greatness of the Lord, which
is the sign of his divinity, is recognized, then the greatness of man, which

(the main contents). [in modern language]. 1090. A. [in modern language]. 1657

This work, which is a translation of Sophocles' Antigone, appeared as the third of a trilogy with Oedipus Tyrannus and The Tragedy of Oedipus.

The action of Antigone begins with the burial of her brother, Polynices. After the tomb is opened, Antigone and Eteocles discover the body, which Antigone, as the next of kin, is to carry back to the city of Thebes. When the two are summoned by the King, they decide to bury the body secretly. When they are caught by the priests, Polynices' son, Orestes, who had been sent to Thebes to get rid of Antigone, comes to their rescue.

prediction.line:
(the main contents). [in modern language]. 1090. A. [in modern language]. 1657

This work, which is a translation of Sophocles' Antigone, appeared as the third of a trilogy with Oedipus Tyrannus and The Tragedy of Oedipus.

The action of Antigone begins with the burial of her brother, Polynices. After the tomb is opened, Antigone and Eteocles discover the body, which Antigone, as the next of kin, is to carry back to the city of Thebes. When the two are summoned by the King, they decide to bury the body secretly. When they are caught by the priests, Polynices' son, Orestes, who had been sent to Thebes to get rid of Antigone, comes to their rescue.

The action of Antigone begins with the burial of her brother, Polynices. When the two are summoned by the King, they decide to bury the body secretly. When they are caught by the priests, Polynices' son, Orestes, who had been sent to Thebes to get rid of Antigone, comes to their rescue.
